<TITLE> Stocks shrug off arrest fallout </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 29 (bdnews24.com) - Stocks finished upbeat Tuesday triggered by speculations and confidence on some bank and pharmaceuticals issues although investors in the morning session were uneasy over reports of arrests of some bigwigs in politics and business. "The market passed a little uneasy day. But known speculations and expectations tagged to some issues remained unaffected," said Yawer Sayeed, chief executive of AIMS of Bangladesh that manages about Tk 550 million in funds. Indices fell sharply in the morning session amid panic selling on arrest reports of seven bigwigs in politics and business. It climbed up steadily until the end. Joint forces on Monday and early Tuesday arrested seven bigwigs in politics and business including Awami League general secretary Abdul Jalil, BNP leader and former state minister for home Lutfozzaman Babar, former president of Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry Abdul Awal Mintoo and Partex Group chairman and former BNP lawmaker MA Hashem. The DGEN or general index added 11.38 points or 0.58 percent to 1948.85. The DSI or all-share price index finished at 1621.85, up 3.73 points or 0.23 percent. Spurred by a rise in Prime Bank, Southeast Bank, Square Pharma and Square Textile, the DSE-20 blue chip index rallied 38.74 points or 2.27 percent to 1738.71. All the indices on the CSE gained. Turnover on the Dhaka Stock Exchange rose to Tk 1.72 billion from Monday's Tk 1.54 billion. Turnover however dropped to Tk 239.36 million from Tk 367.56 million on the Chittagong Stock Exchange. Prime Bank, Power Grid Company of Bangladesh, BRAC Bank, Premier Bank and Southeast Bank were top issues in turnover on the DSE. Aggressive buying drove Prime Bank shares 9.28 percent higher at Tk 865 after reports on its plan to raise authorised capital upto Tk 9000 million from the existing Tk 4000 million. Primes' managing director M Shahjahan Bhuiyan admitted to bdnews24.com on Monday that its board had planned to raise its authorised capital. Prime recorded Tk 225.95 million in turnover. Scoring Tk 158.09 million in turnover, Power Grid ended at 595, 0.45 percent down from the previous day. BRAC Bank that recorded a steady rally in the last couple of days climbed to Tk 771.75. Premier Bank finished unchanged at Tk 327.25. Southeast Bank, fifth leader in turnover, advanced 2.44 percent to Tk 418.75. AB Bank, Prime Bank and Square Textile were major gainers. Pioneer Insurance, Dulamia Cotton and Saleh Carpet led the losers. On the DSE, 38 scrips gained, 151 fell and 15 held steady. On the CSE, 20 issues finished up, 68 lost and six closed unchanged. bdnew
